{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Failure boundary is the heuristic’s local algorithmic quality, not module handoff. A deterministic in-process test can generate coordinate sets, compute heuristic route length, compute optimal length (exact solver for small N / bounded fixtures), and assert ratio <= 1.5. No real OS/network/subprocess needed, and no AI/ML dependency. Higher levels were considered and rejected: Integration is disqualified because the behavior text targets heuristic output quality itself, not cross-module wiring; System/Agentic/Workflow are disqualified because no real infra or model decisions are required.","test_description":"Call the route-heuristic function with representative stop sets (including adversarial layouts) up to 20 stops, compute optimal baseline in-process for each fixture, and assert heuristic_length / optimal_length <= 1.5.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from the distance between consecutive stops and the configured average speed for the road type.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is arithmetic/business-rule correctness at a local function/object boundary: time = distance/speed (plus any documented rounding). It can be validated with pure inputs (segment distances, road type, speed config) and deterministic expected outputs. Integration/System rejected because behavior text does not require real map API, filesystem, network, or subprocess; Agentic/Workflow rejected because no AI/ML output is involved.","test_description":"Test the estimator function with table-driven cases across road types, mixed segments, and rounding edges; assert exact or tolerance-bounded window outputs from provided distances and configured speeds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Single validator rule with deterministic inputs/outputs (total_estimated_time vs remaining_shift_hours). Real failures here are logical boundary/edge errors (equal boundary, float rounding, negative/zero), catchable without module wiring or infra. Higher levels rejected: no concrete behavior text requiring real HTTP/OS/subprocess, and no AI/ML dependency.","test_description":"Invoke the shift-hours validation function with boundary cases (below, equal, above limit) and assert reject/accept plus exact excess-time value when rejected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.93,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address in the list fails geocoding (API returns no results), the service skips that stop and optimizes the remaining addresses, reporting which addresses were skipped.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at module handoff: geocoding result handling -> filtering skipped stops -> optimizer input -> skipped-address reporting. A single-function unit test would miss orchestration defects (e.g., skipped address not reported, optimizer still receives failed stop). Integration is sufficient with an in-process geocoder stub returning one no-result payload and successful results for others. System was considered but rejected because behavior text is specifically about handling an API response shape ('returns no results'), which is reproducible with a stub; no need for real network/HTTP failure semantics. Agentic/Workflow rejected: no AI/ML decision path.","test_description":"Wire service modules with a fake geocoding client that returns no results for one address and coordinates for others; run optimization end-to-end in-process and assert failed address is excluded from route, remaining addresses are optimized, and skipped list contains the failed address.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses in the input list are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior spans at least dedup/consolidation logic plus downstream route construction/visit counting. The failure often emerges when one module consolidates but another still schedules duplicates. Unit tests on dedup alone can miss that cross-module regression, so Integration is the minimum to catch real service-level failure. System rejected: no required real OS/network/subprocess; can run fully in-process. Agentic/Workflow rejected: no AI/ML output dependence.","test_description":"Run the service pipeline in-process with duplicate-address inputs carrying different item sets; assert output stop list has one consolidated stop with merged items and final route visits that address exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.64,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
